================================================================================
LOG TITLE MIGRATION PROPOSAL - STARDATE 2025-12-03
================================================================================

CURRENT SYSTEM ANALYSIS:
• Format: YYYY-MM-DD-descriptive-name.log
• Example: 2025-12-03-merlin-host-transition-analysis.log
• Advantages: Human-readable dates, natural chronological sorting
• Disadvantages: Date-heavy, no sequential progression indicator

PROPOSED NEW SYSTEM:
• Format: report-{COMMIT_COUNT}-{YYYY-MM-DD}-descriptive-name.log
• Example: report-2149-2025-12-03-merlin-host-transition-analysis.log
• Current HEAD commit count: 2149

TECHNICAL IMPLEMENTATION:

**Method 1: Commit Count Based**
```bash
COMMIT_COUNT=$(git rev-list --count HEAD)
FILENAME="report-${COMMIT_COUNT}-$(date +%Y-%m-%d)-${DESCRIPTION}.log"
```

**Method 2: Log Sequence Based** 
```bash
LOG_COUNT=$(ls scottys-journal/logs/ | wc -l)
NEXT_LOG=$((LOG_COUNT + 1))
FILENAME="report-${NEXT_LOG}-$(date +%Y-%m-%d)-${DESCRIPTION}.log"
```

RECOMMENDATION: **Method 1 (Commit Count)**

**Advantages:**
- Provides true chronological progression tied to repository state
- Each report number represents exact repository state when created
- Easy to correlate reports with specific commits
- Natural sequential ordering while maintaining date visibility
- Commit count never decreases, ensuring unique identifiers

**Migration Strategy:**
1. **Preserve Existing**: Keep current logs unchanged for historical continuity
2. **New Format**: Apply new format only to future logs
3. **Transition Period**: Both formats coexist during migration
4. **Script Integration**: Update scotty_create_log() function in logging library

**Updated Logging Function:**
```bash
scotty_create_log() {
    local description="$1"
    local classification="$2"  # "note" or "report"
    local commit_count=$(git rev-list --count HEAD)
    local date_stamp=$(date +%Y-%m-%d)
    local filename="report-${commit_count}-${date_stamp}-${description}.log"
    # ... rest of function
}
```

**Example Progressive Sequence:**
- report-2149-2025-12-03-merlin-host-transition-analysis.log
- report-2150-2025-12-03-captains-operational-reminders.log  
- report-2151-2025-12-04-system-maintenance-completion.log

**Benefits of This Approach:**
- Sequential progression clearly visible
- Date still present for human readability
- Easy to determine "what changed between report 2140 and 2150"
- Commit count provides natural indexing tied to repository evolution
- No conflicts or duplicate numbers possible
- Maintains chronological sorting in file listings

ENGINEERING ASSESSMENT:
This system provides the best of both worlds - sequential indexing with 
preserved date context, while creating a natural correlation between 
reports and repository state progression.

